                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/14511.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-06T19:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 6, 1915—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>393. Department’s 505, March 5, 5 p.m. American 2,500; German 1,800; China 2,000;
                    Turkey same; France 1,900; Spanish 12,000; Cuba 1,200; England 1,000; Italy 700;
                    Japan 500. Other nationalities, 800. The above is only approximate, based on
                    what information I have been able to obtain in such a short time. At the present
                    moment only military trains, where no passengers are admitted, are being
                    operated between Mexico and Vera Cruz, and even these are frequently attacked by
                    opposing factions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliveira.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
